25|$|The {{earliest}} of Mexico's colonial {{artists were}} Spanish-born {{who came to}} Mexico {{in the middle of}} their careers. This included mendicant friars, such as Fray Alonso López de Herrera. Later, most artists were born in Mexico, but trained in European techniques, often from imported engravings. This dependence on imported copies meant <b>that</b> <b>Mexican</b> works preserved styles after they had gone out of fashion in Europe. In the colonial period, artists worked in guilds, not independently. Each guild had its own rules, precepts, and mandates in technique—which did not encourage innovation.|$|E
